    "body": "Hi @edoakes , I'd like to take this on.\n\nI've investigated the root cause and have a fix ready on [this branch](https://github.com/tobby168/ray/tree/claude/investigate-ray-62328-zmBTz) — a single commit touching experimental_mutable_object_manager.cc (and a test).\n\n**Root Cause**\nThere are two independent bugs in OpenSemaphores(), both producing SEM_FAILED → RAY_CHECK_NE crash at line 177:\n\n**Bug 1** — Missing / prefix in semaphore names. GetSemaphoreObjectName / GetSemaphoreHeaderName produce names like \"obj12345-...\" without a leading /. POSIX requires sem_open names to start with /. Linux with glibc ≤ 2.31 (common on DGX Spark / Ubuntu 20.04) enforces this strictly and returns EINVAL. macOS and newer glibc are lenient, which is why this wasn't caught in development.\n\n**Bug 2** — Cross-node reader skips O_CREAT. When semaphores_created == kDone is visible in shared memory (set by the writer on another node), the reader calls sem_open(name, 0) without O_CREAT. The named semaphore was never created on the reader's machine, so sem_open returns ENOENT.\n\n**Fix**\nChanged \"obj\" → \"/obj\" and \"hdr\" → \"/hdr\" in the name helper functions.\nChanged sem_open(name, 0) to sem_open(name, O_CREAT, 0644, 1) in the reader's code path. O_CREAT without O_EXCL opens the existing semaphore intra-node (initial value ignored) and creates it cross-node with the correct initial value of 1.\n**Verification**\nConfirmed the code path is exercised via dag.experimental_compile() (Ray's compiled DAG API, which is what vLLM calls internally) — 20 semaphore pairs created through OpenSemaphores().\nConfirmed installed Ray 2.54.1 has the bug (semaphore names in /dev/shm lack the / prefix).\nC-level reproduction confirmed both EINVAL (Bug 1) and ENOENT (Bug 2) failure modes and their fixes.\nAdded two unit tests: TestSemaphoreNameHasLeadingSlash (Bug 1) and TestCrossNodeSemaphoreCreation (Bug 2).\nCannot fully reproduce the crash on our machine (glibc 2.39 is lenient, single-node only) — final validation requires the reporter's DGX Spark hardware.\n\nHappy to open a PR if this approach looks good.",
